  <!-- Section: Application Process -->
  <section id="application" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Application Process</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The Italian freelancer visa process has two main stages: obtaining the Nulla Osta (work authorization) during the Decreto Flussi window, then applying for the actual visa at an Italian consulate. After arrival, you'll apply for your residence permit (Permesso di Soggiorno).
    </p>

    <ComparisonTable columns={timelineColumns} rows={timelineRows} />

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-8 mb-3">Step-by-Step Guide</h3>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">1</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Monitor Decreto Flussi Announcements</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">The Ministry of Interior typically announces the new year's quotas and application dates in December or January. Follow official channels and expat forums for announcements. Have all documents ready before the window opens.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">2</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Submit Nulla Osta Application</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">On the opening day (often called "Click Day"), submit your application through the Sportello Unico portal. The system can be overwhelmed—start early in the morning. Quotas may fill within hours for popular categories.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">3</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Wait for Nulla Osta Approval</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Processing takes 30-120 days depending on the province. You may be called for an interview at the Sportello Unico. Once approved, you'll receive the authorization document allowing you to apply for the visa.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">4</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Apply for Visa at Italian Consulate</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">With your Nulla Osta in hand, schedule an appointment at the Italian consulate in your home country. Bring all required documents, pay the €116 fee, and submit your application. Processing typically takes 30-90 days.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">5</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Arrive in Italy</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Enter Italy with your visa. You have 8 days to apply for your Permesso di Soggiorno (residence permit). Find your accommodation, confirm your address, and prepare for the next administrative steps.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">6</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Apply for Permesso di Soggiorno</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Go to a post office (Poste Italiane) and request the immigration kit. Complete the forms, attach your documents, and submit the application. You'll receive an appointment date at the Questura (police headquarters).</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">7</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Attend Questura Appointment</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">At the Questura, you'll submit biometrics (fingerprints, photo) and verify your documents. The Permesso is typically issued 30-90 days later. Your post office receipt serves as proof of legal residence while waiting.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">8</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Set Up Your Freelance Business</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Get your Codice Fiscale (tax ID) at the Agenzia delle Entrate. Open a Partita IVA (VAT number) for freelance activity. Find a commercialista to handle taxes. Register with INPS for social security contributions.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4 mt-6">
      <p class="text-blue-800">
        <strong>Patience required:</strong> The Italian bureaucratic process is notoriously slow. Total time from Decreto Flussi opening to receiving your Permesso can be 6-12 months. Plan accordingly and don't book one-way flights until your visa is actually issued.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

