  <!-- Section: Common Mistakes -->
  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Missing the Decreto Flussi Window</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">The quota system means timing is everything. If you're not online when the application window opens (often at 9:00 AM Italian time), you may miss out entirely. Self-employment quotas are limited and can fill within hours. Set multiple alarms and have a fast internet connection.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Choosing Wrong Visa Type</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">If you only work with foreign clients, the Digital Nomad Visa (€28,000/year minimum, no quota) may be easier than Lavoro Autonomo. If you want Italian clients, only Lavoro Autonomo works. Understand the differences before applying—switching mid-process causes delays.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Not Hiring a Commercialista</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Italian tax law is complex, especially the Regime Forfettario rules, INPS calculations, and quarterly filings. The €100-250/month for a commercialista is essential—DIY tax filing often results in errors, penalties, and lost deductions. Find one before you arrive.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Underestimating INPS Contributions</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">While the 5-15% flat tax sounds attractive, INPS social security contributions add roughly 26% on top. Your effective tax rate is 31-41%, not 5-15%. Budget for both when calculating your take-home income.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Dropping Insurance Before SSN Confirmation</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">SSN (public healthcare) enrollment can take months after you start paying INPS. Keep your private insurance active until you have your tessera sanitaria and verified enrollment. Gaps in coverage can be problematic for permit renewals.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Healthcare in Italy -->
  <section id="healthcare" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Healthcare in Italy</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Italy has a high-quality public healthcare system (Servizio Sanitario Nazionale or SSN) that ranks among the best in Europe. As a legal resident paying INPS contributions, you should eventually qualify for SSN coverage—though initially you'll rely on private insurance.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">What's Covered</h3>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
      <div class="border border-green-200 bg-green-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-green-900 mb-3">SSN Coverage (Once Enrolled)</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-green-800">
          <li>✓ GP (medico di base) consultations</li>
          <li>✓ Specialist referrals</li>
          <li>✓ Hospital care and surgeries</li>
          <li>✓ Prescription medications (small copay)</li>
          <li>✓ Emergency care</li>
          <li>✓ Maternity care</li>
          <li>✓ Mental health services</li>
          <li>✓ Preventive screenings</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-amber-200 bg-amber-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-3">Often Requires Private Insurance</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-amber-800">
          <li>• Dental care (limited SSN coverage)</li>
          <li>• Vision care and glasses</li>
          <li>• Faster specialist appointments</li>
          <li>• Private hospital rooms</li>
          <li>• Alternative medicine</li>
          <li>• Non-essential procedures</li>
          <li>• Coverage while abroad</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">How to Access Healthcare</h3>

    <div class="space-y-4 mb-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Getting Your Medico di Base</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Once enrolled in SSN, you choose a general practitioner (medico di base) from a list at your local ASL. This doctor handles routine care and referrals to specialists. Most GPs have limited English—consider this when choosing.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Specialist Appointments</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">For specialists under SSN, you need a referral from your medico di base. Wait times can be long (weeks to months). Many Italians use private insurance or pay out-of-pocket (€80-200) for faster access to specialists.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Emergencies</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Call 118 for emergencies. Hospital emergency rooms (Pronto Soccorso) are available 24/7 and treat everyone regardless of insurance status. For urgent but non-emergency care, some cities have guardia medica (medical guard) services.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4">
      <p class="text-blue-800">
        <strong>Language tip:</strong> While doctors in major cities may speak some English, healthcare in Italy largely operates in Italian. Consider learning basic medical vocabulary or bringing a translator app. In emergencies, hospitals usually find someone who speaks English, but routine care benefits from Italian language skills.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What is the minimum income for Italy's freelancer visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          The Lavoro Autonomo visa requires just €8,500/year gross minimum—one of the lowest thresholds in Europe. However, you must demonstrate that your freelance activity is sustainable. If you earn significantly more, consider whether the Digital Nomad Visa (€28,000/year, foreign clients only) might be simpler since it avoids the quota system.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How does the Decreto Flussi quota system work?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Each year, Italy sets quotas for different types of work permits. Self-employment quotas are limited—often just a few thousand slots nationally. Applications open on a specific date (usually January-March), and slots can fill within hours. You must apply during this window; missing it means waiting until next year.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I need to speak Italian for the freelancer visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Italian language is not a visa requirement. However, daily life—dealing with bureaucracy, healthcare, landlords, and the Questura—is significantly easier with Italian. Many freelancers manage in English in major cities like Milan and Rome, but expect challenges. Basic Italian is highly recommended.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What is the Regime Forfettario and should I use it?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          The Regime Forfettario is a flat-rate tax scheme offering 5% tax for your first 5 years (then 15%), instead of progressive rates up to 43%. It's available to freelancers earning under €85,000/year. Most freelancers should use it—your commercialista can confirm eligibility. Note: INPS contributions (~26%) are separate and still apply.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I work with Italian clients on the Digital Nomad Visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          No. The Digital Nomad Visa explicitly requires that your income comes from clients or employers outside Italy. If you want to serve the Italian market, you need the Lavoro Autonomo visa. Mixing client types can jeopardize your visa status.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How long until I can get permanent residence?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          After 5 years of continuous legal residence in Italy, you can apply for the EU long-term residence permit (Permesso di Soggiorno UE per soggiornanti di lungo periodo). Requirements include: stable income, adequate accommodation, Italian language proficiency, and no significant absences from Italy.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

